<p>
<h3>DIRECTORY STACK STRUCTURE FOR PUSHD & POPD :</h3>

Please pay attention on this topic, it may be bit confusing at the beginning but it is all about stack.
<br>

<h4>Example :</h4>


Create a directory as below ,
<br>
$mkdir -p A/B/C/D/E     ----------->1 <br>
$cd A                             ----------->2<br>
$pushd B                       ----------->3<br>
$cd C                             ----------->4<br>
$pushd D                       ----------->5<br>
$cd E                             ----------->6<br>



$pwd<br>

You will be in the last directory E.<br>

$popd                           ------------->7<br>
$popd                           ------------->8<br>
$popd   [ This will return a warning message like ] bash: popd: directory stack empty ]                         ------------->9<br>

During the steps 3 & 5 , we will the stack structure as below.<br>



</p>



